# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: audio-equalization
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:audio-equalization/equalization-audio] Most hi-fi equipment uses relatively simple filters to make bass and treble adjustments.
[src:audio-equalization/equalization-audio] Graphic and parametric equalizers have much more flexibility in tailoring the frequency content of an audio signal.
[src:audio-equalization/equalization-audio] Broadcast and recording studios use sophisticated equalizers capable of much more detailed adjustments, such as eliminating unwanted sounds or making certain instruments or voices more prominent.
[src:audio-equalization/equalization-audio] Equalizers are used in recording and radio studios, production control rooms, and live sound reinforcement and in instrument amplifiers, such as guitar amplifiers, to correct or adjust the response of microphones, instrument pickups, loudspeakers, and hall acoustics.
[src:audio-equalization/equalization-audio] Equalization may also be used to eliminate or reduce unwanted sounds (e.g., low-frequency hum coming from a guitar amplifier), make certain instruments or voices more (or less) prominent, enhance particular aspects of an instrument's tone, or combat feedback (howling) in a public address system.
[src:audio-equalization/equalization-audio] Equalizers are also used in music production to adjust the timbre of individual instruments and voices by adjusting their frequency content and to fit individual instruments within the overall frequency spectrum of the mix.
[src:audio-equalization/equalization-audio] The concept of equalization was first applied in correcting the frequency response of telephone lines using passive filters; this was prior to the invention of electronic amplification.
[src:audio-equalization/equalization-audio] Initially, equalization was used to compensate for the uneven frequency response of an electric system by applying a filter having the opposite response, thus restoring the fidelity of the transmission.
[src:audio-equalization/equalization-audio] A plot of the system's net frequency response would be a flat line, as its response at any frequency would be equal to its response at any other frequency.
[src:audio-equalization/equalization-audio] Later the concept was applied in audio engineering to adjust the frequency response in recording, reproduction, and live sound reinforcement systems.
[src:audio-equalization/equalization-audio] Sound engineers correct the frequency response of a sound system so that the frequency balance of the music as heard through speakers better matches the original performance picked up by a microphone.
[src:audio-equalization/equalization-audio] Audio amplifiers have long had filters or controls to modify their frequency response.
[src:audio-equalization/equalization-audio] These are most often in the form of variable bass and treble controls, and switches to apply low-cut or high-cut filters for elimination of low-frequency *rumble* and high-frequency *hiss* respectively.
[src:audio-equalization/equalization-audio] Graphic equalizers and other equipment developed for improving fidelity have since been used by recording engineers to modify frequency responses for aesthetic reasons.
[src:audio-equalization/equalization-audio] Hence in the field of audio electronics, the term *equalization* is now broadly used to describe the application of such filters regardless of intent.
[src:audio-equalization/equalization-audio] This broad definition, therefore, includes all linear filters at the disposal of a listener or engineer.
[src:audio-equalization/equalization-audio] Audio equalization can be based on user-selected audio modes, such as *music*, *movie*, *drama*, *dialogue*, and *gaming*.
[src:audio-equalization/equalization-audio] A **British EQ** or **British style equalizer** is one with similar properties to those on mixing consoles made in the UK by companies such as Amek, Neve and Soundcraft from the 1950s through to the 1970s.
[src:audio-equalization/equalization-audio] Later on, as other manufacturers started to market their products, these British companies began touting their equalizers as being a cut above the rest.
[src:audio-equalization/equalization-audio] Today, many non-British companies such as Behringer and Mackie advertise British EQ on their equipment.
[src:audio-equalization/equalization-audio] A British-style EQ seeks to replicate the qualities of the expensive British mixing consoles.
[src:audio-equalization/equalization-audio] Filtering audio frequencies dates back at least to acoustic telegraphy and multiplexing in general.
[src:audio-equalization/equalization-audio] Audio electronic equipment evolved to incorporate filtering elements as consoles in radio stations began to be used for recording as well as broadcasting.
[src:audio-equalization/equalization-audio] Early filters included basic bass and treble controls featuring fixed frequency centers and fixed levels of cut or boost.
[src:audio-equalization/equalization-audio] These filters worked over broad frequency ranges.
[src:audio-equalization/equalization-audio] Variable equalization in audio reproduction was first used by John Volkman working at RCA in the 1920s.
[src:audio-equalization/equalization-audio] That system was used to equalize a motion picture theater sound playback system.
[src:audio-equalization/equalization-audio] The Langevin EQ-251-A, designed by Art Davis, was the first equalizer to use slide controls.
[src:audio-equalization/equalization-audio] It featured two passive equalization sections, a bass shelving filter, and a pass band filter.
[src:audio-equalization/equalization-audio] Each filter had switchable frequencies and used a 15-position slide switch to adjust cut or boost.
[src:audio-equalization/equalization-audio] The passive design required 14 dB of make-up gain.
[src:audio-equalization/equalization-audio] Born in Salt Lake City, Davis worked in Southern California most of his life for a series of companies including Cinema Engineering (from 1938), Langevin, Electrodyne, Cetec and Altec.
[src:audio-equalization/equalization-audio] The first true graphic equalizer was the type 7080, an active tube device developed in the 1950s by Davis's Cinema Engineering company.
[src:audio-equalization/equalization-audio] It featured six bands, each 1.5 octaves wide, with a boost or cut range of 8 dB.
[src:audio-equalization/equalization-audio] It used a slide switch to adjust each band in 1 dB steps.
[src:audio-equalization/equalization-audio] Three summing amps smoothly restored the gain lost in the filter circuits.
[src:audio-equalization/equalization-audio] Davis followed this in 1961 with the Langevin EQ-252-A, having seven sliders, then reworked it for Altec Lansing to create the Model 9062A EQ, which sold well into the 1970s.
[src:audio-equalization/equalization-audio] In 1967 Davis developed the first 1/3 octave variable notch filter set, the Altec-Lansing "Acousta-Voice" system.
[src:audio-equalization/equalization-audio] In 1966, Burgess Macneal and George Massenburg envisioned a tunable EQ for a new recording console.
[src:audio-equalization/equalization-audio] Bob Meushaw, a friend of Massenburg, built the equalizer.
[src:audio-equalization/equalization-audio] I wrote and delivered the AES paper on Parametrics at the Los Angeles show in 1972...
[src:audio-equalization/equalization-audio] Flickinger introduced the first parametric equalizer in early 1971.
[src:audio-equalization/equalization-audio] His design leveraged a high-performance op-amp of his own design, the 535 series to achieve filtering circuits that were before impossible.
[src:audio-equalization/equalization-audio] Flickinger's patent from early in 1971 showed the circuit topology that would come to dominate audio equalization until the present day, as well as the theoretical underpinnings of the elegant circuit.
[src:audio-equalization/equalization-audio] Instead of slide potentiometers working on individual bands of frequency, or rotary switches, Flickinger's circuit allowed arbitrary selection of frequency and cut or boost level in three overlapping bands over the entire audio spectrum.
[src:audio-equalization/equalization-audio] Six knobs on his early EQs would control these sweepable filters.
[src:audio-equalization/equalization-audio] Up to six switches were incorporated to select shelving on the high and low bands, and bypassing for any unused band for the purest signal path.
[src:audio-equalization/equalization-audio] Similar designs appeared soon thereafter from George Massenburg (in 1972) and Burgess McNeal from ITI corp.
[src:audio-equalization/equalization-audio] In May 1972 Massenburg used the term *parametric equalization* in a paper presented at the 42nd convention of the Audio Engineering Society.
[src:audio-equalization/equalization-audio] Most channel equalization on mixing consoles made from 1971 to the present day rely upon the designs of Flickinger, Massenburg and McNeal in either semi or fully-parametric topology.
[src:audio-equalization/equalization-audio] In the late 1990s and in the 2000s, parametric equalizers became increasingly available as digital signal processing (DSP) equipment, usually in the form of plug-ins for various digital audio workstations.
[src:audio-equalization/equalization-audio] Standalone outboard gear versions of DSP parametric equalizers were also quickly introduced after the software versions.
[src:audio-equalization/equalization-audio] Although the range of equalization functions is governed by the theory of linear filters, the adjustment of those functions and the flexibility with which they can be adjusted varies according to the topology of the circuitry and controls presented to the user.
[src:audio-equalization/equalization-audio] Shelving controls are usually simple first-order filter functions that alter the relative gains between frequencies much higher and much lower than the cutoff frequencies.
[src:audio-equalization/equalization-audio] A *low shelf*, such as the bass control on most hi-fi equipment, is adjusted to affect the gain of lower frequencies while having no effect well above its cutoff frequency.
[src:audio-equalization/equalization-audio] A *high shelf*, such as a treble control, adjusts the gain of higher frequencies only.
[src:audio-equalization/equalization-audio] These are broad adjustments designed more to increase the listener's satisfaction than to provide actual equalization in the strict sense of the term.
[src:audio-equalization/equalization-audio] A parametric equalizer has one or more sections each of which implements a second-order filter function.
[src:audio-equalization/equalization-audio] In a *semi-parametric* equalizer, the bandwidth is preset by the designer.
[src:audio-equalization/equalization-audio] In a *quasi-parametric* equalizer, the user is given limited switchable options for bandwidth.
[src:audio-equalization/equalization-audio] A graphic equalizer also implements second-order filter functions in a more user-friendly manner, but with somewhat less flexibility.
[src:audio-equalization/equalization-audio] This equipment is based on a bank of filters covering the audio spectrum in up to 31 frequency bands.
[src:audio-equalization/equalization-audio] Each second-order filter has a fixed center frequency and Q factor, but an adjustable level.
[src:audio-equalization/equalization-audio] The user can raise or lower each slider in order to visually approximate a *graph* of the intended frequency response.
[src:audio-equalization/equalization-audio] A first-order low-pass or high-pass filter has a standard response curve that reduces the unwanted frequencies well above or below the cutoff frequency with a slope of 6 dB per octave.
[src:audio-equalization/equalization-audio] A second-order filter will reduce those frequencies with a slope of 12 dB per octave and moreover, may be designed with a higher Q or finite zeros in order to effect an even steeper response around the cutoff frequency.
[src:audio-equalization/equalization-audio] For instance, a second-order *low-pass notch* filter section only reduces (rather than eliminates) very high frequencies, but has a steep response falling to zero at a specific frequency (the so-called *notch frequency*).
[src:audio-equalization/equalization-audio] Such a filter might be ideal, for instance, in completely removing the 19 kHz FM stereo subcarrier pilot signal while helping to cut even higher frequency subcarrier components remaining from the stereo demultiplexer.
[src:audio-equalization/equalization-audio] In addition to adjusting the relative amplitude of frequency bands, an audio equalizer usually alters the relative phases of those frequencies.
[src:audio-equalization/equalization-audio] While the human ear is not as sensitive to the phase of audio frequencies, music professionals may favor certain equalizers because of how they affect the timbre of the musical content by way of audible phase artifacts.
[src:audio-equalization/equalization-audio] A high-pass filter is a filter, an electronic circuit or device, that passes higher frequencies well but attenuates lower-frequency components.
[src:audio-equalization/equalization-audio] A low-pass filter passes low-frequency components of signals while attenuating higher frequencies.
[src:audio-equalization/equalization-audio] In audio applications, these high-pass and low-pass filters are frequently termed *low cut* and *high cut*, respectively, to emphasize their effect on the original signal.
[src:audio-equalization/equalization-audio] For instance, sometimes audio equipment will include a switch labeled *high cut* or described as a *hiss filter* (hiss being high-frequency noise).
[src:audio-equalization/equalization-audio] In the phonograph era, many stereos would include a switch to introduce a high-pass (low cut) filter, often called a *rumble filter*, to eliminate infrasonic frequencies.
[src:audio-equalization/equalization-audio] High and low-pass filters are used in audio crossovers to direct energy to the speaker drivers capable of reproducing it.
[src:audio-equalization/equalization-audio] For instance, a low-pass filter is used in the signal chain before a subwoofer to ensure that only deep bass frequencies reach the subwoofer.
[src:audio-equalization/equalization-audio] While high-pass and low-pass filters are useful for removing unwanted signal above or below a set frequency, shelving filters can be used to reduce or increase signals above or below a set frequency.
[src:audio-equalization/equalization-audio] Shelving filters are used as common tone controls (bass and treble) found in consumer audio equipment such as home stereos, and on guitar amplifiers and bass amplifiers.
[src:audio-equalization/equalization-audio] These implement a first-order response and provide an adjustable boost or cut to frequencies above or below a certain point.
[src:audio-equalization/equalization-audio] where *fp* and *fz* are called the pole and zero frequencies, respectively.
[src:audio-equalization/equalization-audio] Turning down the treble control increases *fz* and decreases *fp* so that frequencies higher than *fp* are attenuated.
[src:audio-equalization/equalization-audio] Turning up the treble control increases *fp* and decreases *fz* so that frequencies higher than *fz* are boosted.
[src:audio-equalization/equalization-audio] Setting the treble control at the center sets *fz* = *fp* so that |*H*(*f*)|2 = 1 and the circuit has no effect.
[src:audio-equalization/equalization-audio] At most, the slope of the filter response in the transition region will be 6 dB per octave.
[src:audio-equalization/equalization-audio] In this case, the inclusion of the leading factor simply indicates that the response at frequencies much higher than *fz* or *fp* is unity and that only bass frequencies are affected.
[src:audio-equalization/equalization-audio] A high shelving control in which *fz* is set to infinity, or a low shelving response in which *fz* is set to zero, implements a first-order low-pass or high-pass filter, respectively.
[src:audio-equalization/equalization-audio] However, the usual tone controls have a more limited range, since their purpose is not to eliminate any frequencies but only to achieve a greater balance when, for instance, the treble is lacking and the sound is not crisp.
[src:audio-equalization/equalization-audio] Since the range of possible responses from shelving filters is so limited, some audio engineers considered shelving controls inadequate for equalization tasks.
[src:audio-equalization/equalization-audio] On some bass amps and DI boxes, the units provide both low and high shelving controls and additional equalization controls.
[src:audio-equalization/equalization-audio] In the **graphic equalizer**, or **GEQ** for short, the input signal is sent to a bank of filters.
[src:audio-equalization/equalization-audio] Each filter passes the portion of the signal present in its own frequency range or *band*.
[src:audio-equalization/equalization-audio] The amplitude passed by each filter is adjusted using a slide control to boost or cut frequency components passed by that filter.
[src:audio-equalization/equalization-audio] The vertical position of each slider thus indicates the gain applied to that frequency band, so that the sliders resemble a *graph* of the equalizer's response plotted versus frequency.
[src:audio-equalization/equalization-audio] The number of frequency channels may be matched to the requirements of the intended application.
[src:audio-equalization/equalization-audio] A car audio equalizer might have a total of five to ten frequency bands.
[src:audio-equalization/equalization-audio] An equalizer for professional live sound reinforcement typically has some 25 to 31 bands, for more precise control of feedback problems and equalization of room modes.
[src:audio-equalization/equalization-audio] Such an equalizer is called a 1/3-octave equalizer (spoken informally as "*third-octave* EQ") because the center frequencies of its filters are spaced one third of an octave apart, three filters to an octave.
[src:audio-equalization/equalization-audio] Equalizers with half as many filters per octave are common where less precise control is required—this design is called a 2/3-octave equalizer.
[src:audio-equalization/equalization-audio] A variant of the parametric equalizer is the semi-parametric equalizer, a sweepable filter.
[src:audio-equalization/equalization-audio] It allows users to control the gain and frequency but uses a pre-set bandwidth.
[src:audio-equalization/equalization-audio] In some cases, semi-parametric equalizers allow the user to select between a wide and a narrow preset bandwidth.
[src:audio-equalization/equalization-audio] The responses of linear filters are mathematically described in terms of their transfer function or, in layman's terms, frequency response.
[src:audio-equalization/equalization-audio] A transfer function can be decomposed as a combination of *first-order* responses and *second-order* responses (implemented as *biquad* sections).
[src:audio-equalization/equalization-audio] These can be described according to their *pole* and *zero* frequencies, which are complex numbers in the case of second-order responses.
[src:audio-equalization/equalization-audio] A first-order filter can alter the response of frequencies above and below a point.
[src:audio-equalization/equalization-audio] In the transition region, the filter response will have a slope of up to 6 dB per octave.
[src:audio-equalization/equalization-audio] The bass and treble controls in a hi-fi system are each a first-order filter in which the balance of frequencies above and below a point are varied using a single knob.
[src:audio-equalization/equalization-audio] A special case of first-order filters is a first-order high-pass or low-pass filter in which the 6 dB per octave cut of low or high frequencies extends indefinitely.
[src:audio-equalization/equalization-audio] These are the simplest of all filters to implement individually, requiring only a capacitor and resistor.
[src:audio-equalization/equalization-audio] Second-order filters are capable of resonance (or anti-resonance) around a particular frequency.
[src:audio-equalization/equalization-audio] The response of a second-order filter is specified not only by its frequency but also by its Q; a higher Q corresponds to a sharper response (smaller bandwidth) around a particular center frequency.
[src:audio-equalization/equalization-audio] For instance, the red response in the accompanying image cuts frequencies around 100 Hz with a higher Q than the blue response, which boosts frequencies around 1000 Hz.
[src:audio-equalization/equalization-audio] where *F*0 is the resonant frequency of the second-order filter.
[src:audio-equalization/equalization-audio] *BW* is the bandwidth expressed in the same frequency unit that *F*0 is.
[src:audio-equalization/equalization-audio] Low Q filter responses (where *Q* < 1⁄2) are not said to be resonant, and the above formula for bandwidth does not apply.
[src:audio-equalization/equalization-audio] A second-order filter response with *Q* of less than 1/2 can be decomposed into two first-order filter functions, a low-cut and a high-cut (or boost).
[src:audio-equalization/equalization-audio] Of more interest are resonant filter functions which can boost (or cut) a narrow range of frequencies.
[src:audio-equalization/equalization-audio] In addition to specifying the center frequency *F*0 and the Q, the specification of the filter's zeros determines how much that frequency band will be boosted (or cut).
[src:audio-equalization/equalization-audio] Thus, a parametric equalizer section will have three controls for its center frequency *F*0, bandwidth or Q, and the amount of boost or cut usually expressed in dB.
[src:audio-equalization/equalization-audio] The range of second-order filter functions is important because any analog filter function can be decomposed into a (usually small) number of these (plus, perhaps, simpler first-order responses).
[src:audio-equalization/equalization-audio] These are implemented directly by each section of a parametric equalizer, where they are explicitly adjusted.
[src:audio-equalization/equalization-audio] And each element of a graphic equalizer based on a filter bank includes one such element per band whose Q and *F*0 is not adjustable by the user.
[src:audio-equalization/equalization-audio] In sound recording, equalization may be used to adjust frequency responses for practical or aesthetic reasons, where the result typically is intentionally *unequal* volume levels for the different frequencies.
[src:audio-equalization/equalization-audio] For example, equalization is used to modify an instrument's sound or make certain instruments and sounds more prominent.
[src:audio-equalization/equalization-audio] A recording engineer may use an equalizer to make some high-pitches in a vocal part louder while making low-pitches in a drum part quieter.
[src:audio-equalization/equalization-audio] Equalization is commonly used to increase the *depth* of a mix, creating the impression that some sounds in a mono or stereo mix are farther away or closer than others.
[src:audio-equalization/equalization-audio] Equalization is also commonly used to give tracks with similar frequency components complementary spectral contours, known as **mirrored equalization**.
[src:audio-equalization/equalization-audio] Selected components of parts that would otherwise compete, such as bass guitar and kick drum, are boosted in one part and cut in the other, and vice versa, so that they both stand out.
[src:audio-equalization/equalization-audio] Equalizers can correct problems posed by a room's acoustics, as an auditorium will generally have an uneven frequency response, especially due to standing waves and acoustic dampening.
[src:audio-equalization/equalization-audio] For instance, the frequency response of a room may be analyzed using a spectrum analyzer and a pink noise generator.
[src:audio-equalization/equalization-audio] Then a graphic equalizer can be adjusted to compensate for the room's acoustics.
[src:audio-equalization/equalization-audio] Such compensation can also be applied to tweak the sound quality of a recording studio in addition to its use in live sound reinforcement systems and even home hi-fi systems.
[src:audio-equalization/equalization-audio] During live events where signals from microphones are amplified and sent to speaker systems, equalization is not only used to adjust the frequency response for a natural sound but may also be useful in eliminating feedback.
[src:audio-equalization/equalization-audio] But because the feedback is troublesome at a particular frequency, it is possible to cut the gain only around that frequency.
[src:audio-equalization/equalization-audio] This can be done using a parametric equalizer tuned to the frequency.
[src:audio-equalization/equalization-audio] By adjusting the equalizer attenuation in a narrow bandwidth (high Q), most other frequency components will not be affected.
[src:audio-equalization/equalization-audio] The extreme case when the signal at the filter's center frequency is eliminated is known as a notch filter.
[src:audio-equalization/equalization-audio] An equalizer can be used to correct or modify the frequency response of a loudspeaker system rather than designing the speaker itself to have the desired response.
[src:audio-equalization/equalization-audio] For instance, the Bose 901 speaker system does not use separate larger and smaller drivers to cover the bass and treble frequencies.
[src:audio-equalization/equalization-audio] Instead, it uses nine drivers, all of the same four-inch diameter.
[src:audio-equalization/equalization-audio] However, this speaker system is sold with an active equalizer which, when inserted into the signal chain, produces the response intended by the manufacturer.
[src:audio-equalization/equalization-audio] Tone controls (usually designated *bass* and *treble*) are simple shelving filters included in most hi-fi equipment for gross adjustment of the frequency balance.
[src:audio-equalization/equalization-audio] The bass control may be used, for instance, to increase the drum and bass parts at a dance party, or to reduce annoying bass sounds when listening to a person speaking.
[src:audio-equalization/equalization-audio] The treble control might be used to give the percussion a sharper or more *brilliant* sound, or can be used to cut such high frequencies when they have been overemphasized in the program material, to reduce accompanying high-frequency noise, or simply to accommodate a listener's preference.
[src:audio-equalization/equalization-audio] A *rumble filter* is a high-pass (low cut) filter with a cutoff typically in the 20 to 40 Hz range; this is the low frequency end of human hearing.
[src:audio-equalization/equalization-audio] *Rumble* is a type of low-frequency noise produced in record players and turntables, particularly older or low-quality models.
[src:audio-equalization/equalization-audio] The rumble filter prevents this noise from being amplified and sent to the loudspeakers.
[src:audio-equalization/equalization-audio] Some cassette decks have a switchable *subsonic filter* feature that does the same thing for recordings.
[src:audio-equalization/equalization-audio] A crossover network is a system of filters designed to direct electrical energy separately to the woofer and tweeter of a 2-way speaker system (and also to the mid-range speaker of a 3-way system).
[src:audio-equalization/equalization-audio] This is most often built into the speaker enclosure and hidden from the user.
[src:audio-equalization/equalization-audio] However, in bi-amplification, these filters operate on the line-level audio signals, sending the low-frequency and high-frequency signal components to separate amplifiers, which connect to the woofers and tweeters, respectively.
[src:audio-equalization/equalization-audio] Equalization is used in a reciprocal manner in certain communication channels and recording technologies.
[src:audio-equalization/equalization-audio] The original music is passed through a particular filter to alter its frequency balance, followed by the channel or recording process.
[src:audio-equalization/equalization-audio] At the end of the channel or when the recording is played, a complementary filter is inserted which precisely compensates for the original filter and recovers the original waveform.
[src:audio-equalization/equalization-audio] For instance, FM broadcasting uses a pre-emphasis filter to boost the high frequencies before transmission, and every receiver includes a matching de-emphasis filter to restore them.
[src:audio-equalization/equalization-audio] The white noise that is introduced by background noise picked up by the radio is then also de-emphasized at the higher frequencies (where it is most noticeable) along with the pre-emphasized program, making the noise less audible.
[src:audio-equalization/equalization-audio] Tape recorders use the same approach to reduce tape hiss while maintaining fidelity.
[src:audio-equalization/equalization-audio] In contrast, in the production of vinyl records, a filter is used to reduce the amplitude of low frequencies, which otherwise produce large amplitudes on the tracks of a record.
[src:audio-equalization/equalization-audio] This allows the groove to take up less physical space, fitting more music on the record.
[src:audio-equalization/equalization-audio] The preamplifier attached to the phono cartridge has a complementary filter boosting those low frequencies, following the standard RIAA equalization curve.
[src:audio-equalization/filter-signal-processing] In signal processing, a **filter** is a device or process that removes some unwanted components or features from a signal.
[src:audio-equalization/filter-signal-processing] Filtering is a class of signal processing, the defining feature of filters being the complete or partial suppression of some aspect of the signal.
[src:audio-equalization/filter-signal-processing] Most often, this means removing some frequencies or frequency bands.
[src:audio-equalization/filter-signal-processing] However, filters do not exclusively act in the frequency domain; especially in the field of image processing many other targets for filtering exist.
[src:audio-equalization/filter-signal-processing] Correlations can be removed for certain frequency components and not for others without having to act in the frequency domain.
[src:audio-equalization/filter-signal-processing] Filters are widely used in electronics and telecommunication, in radio, television, audio recording, radar, control systems, music synthesis, image processing, computer graphics, and structural dynamics.
[src:audio-equalization/filter-signal-processing] There are many different bases of classifying filters and these overlap in many different ways; there is no simple hierarchical classification.
[src:audio-equalization/filter-signal-processing] The modern design methodology for linear continuous-time filters is called network synthesis.
[src:audio-equalization/filter-signal-processing] The difference between these filter families is that they all use a different polynomial function to approximate to the ideal filter response.
[src:audio-equalization/filter-signal-processing] This results in each having a different transfer function.
[src:audio-equalization/filter-signal-processing] Another older, less-used methodology is the image parameter method.
[src:audio-equalization/filter-signal-processing] Filters designed by this methodology are archaically called "wave filters".
[src:audio-equalization/filter-signal-processing] One important application of filters is in telecommunication.
[src:audio-equalization/filter-signal-processing] Many telecommunication systems use frequency-division multiplexing, where the system designers divide a wide frequency band into many narrower frequency bands called "slots" or "channels", and each stream of information is allocated one of those channels.
[src:audio-equalization/filter-signal-processing] The people who design the filters at each transmitter and each receiver try to balance passing the desired signal through as accurately as possible, keeping interference to and from other cooperating transmitters and noise sources outside the system as low as possible, at reasonable cost.
[src:audio-equalization/filter-signal-processing] Multilevel and multiphase digital modulation systems require filters that have flat phase delay—are linear phase in the passband—to preserve pulse integrity in the time domain, giving less intersymbol interference than other kinds of filters.
[src:audio-equalization/filter-signal-processing] Filters can be built in a number of different technologies.
[src:audio-equalization/filter-signal-processing] The same transfer function can be realised in several different ways, that is the mathematical properties of the filter are the same but the physical properties are quite different.
[src:audio-equalization/filter-signal-processing] Often the components in different technologies are directly analogous to each other and fulfill the same role in their respective filters.
[src:audio-equalization/filter-signal-processing] For instance, the resistors, inductors and capacitors of electronics correspond respectively to dampers, masses and springs in mechanics.
[src:audio-equalization/filter-signal-processing] Likewise, there are corresponding components in distributed-element filters.
[src:audio-equalization/filter-signal-processing] Digital signal processing allows the inexpensive construction of a wide variety of filters.
[src:audio-equalization/filter-signal-processing] The signal is sampled and an analog-to-digital converter turns the signal into a stream of numbers.
[src:audio-equalization/filter-signal-processing] A computer program running on a CPU or a specialized DSP (or less often running on a hardware implementation of the algorithm) calculates an output number stream.
[src:audio-equalization/filter-signal-processing] This output can be converted to a signal by passing it through a digital-to-analog converter.
[src:audio-equalization/filter-signal-processing] There are problems with noise introduced by the conversions, but these can be controlled and limited for many useful filters.
[src:audio-equalization/filter-signal-processing] Due to the sampling involved, the input signal must be of limited frequency content or aliasing will occur.
[src:audio-equalization/filter-signal-processing] In the late 1930s, engineers realized that small mechanical systems made of rigid materials such as quartz would acoustically resonate at radio frequencies, i.e. from audible frequencies (sound) up to several hundred megahertz.
[src:audio-equalization/filter-signal-processing] Some early resonators were made of steel, but quartz quickly became favored.
[src:audio-equalization/filter-signal-processing] The biggest advantage of quartz is that it is piezoelectric.
[src:audio-equalization/filter-signal-processing] This means that quartz resonators can directly convert their own mechanical motion into electrical signals.
[src:audio-equalization/filter-signal-processing] Quartz also has a very low coefficient of thermal expansion which means that quartz resonators can produce stable frequencies over a wide temperature range.
[src:audio-equalization/filter-signal-processing] Quartz crystal filters have much higher quality factors than LCR filters.
[src:audio-equalization/filter-signal-processing] When higher stabilities are required, the crystals and their driving circuits may be mounted in a "crystal oven" to control the temperature.
[src:audio-equalization/filter-signal-processing] For very narrow band filters, sometimes several crystals are operated in series.
[src:audio-equalization/filter-signal-processing] A large number of crystals can be collapsed into a single component, by mounting comb-shaped evaporations of metal on a quartz crystal.
[src:audio-equalization/filter-signal-processing] In this scheme, a "tapped delay line" reinforces the desired frequencies as the sound waves flow across the surface of the quartz crystal.
[src:audio-equalization/filter-signal-processing] The tapped delay line has become a general scheme of making high-*Q* filters in many different ways.
[src:audio-equalization/filter-signal-processing] SAW (surface acoustic wave) filters are electromechanical devices commonly used in radio frequency applications.
[src:audio-equalization/filter-signal-processing] Electrical signals are converted to a mechanical wave in a device constructed of a piezoelectric crystal or ceramic; this wave is delayed as it propagates across the device, before being converted back to an electrical signal by further electrodes.
[src:audio-equalization/filter-signal-processing] The delayed outputs are recombined to produce a direct analog implementation of a finite impulse response filter.
[src:audio-equalization/filter-signal-processing] This hybrid filtering technique is also found in an analog sampled filter.
[src:audio-equalization/filter-signal-processing] SAW filters are limited to frequencies up to 3 GHz.
[src:audio-equalization/filter-signal-processing] The filters were developed by Professor Ted Paige and others.
[src:audio-equalization/filter-signal-processing] BAW (bulk acoustic wave) filters are electromechanical devices.
[src:audio-equalization/filter-signal-processing] BAW filters can implement ladder or lattice filters.
[src:audio-equalization/filter-signal-processing] BAW filters typically operate at frequencies from around 2 to around 16 GHz, and may be smaller or thinner than equivalent SAW filters.
[src:audio-equalization/filter-signal-processing] Two main variants of BAW filters are making their way into devices: thin-film bulk acoustic resonator or FBAR and solid mounted bulk acoustic resonators (SMRs).
[src:audio-equalization/filter-signal-processing] Another method of filtering, at microwave frequencies from 800 MHz to about 5 GHz, is to use a synthetic single crystal yttrium iron garnet sphere made of a chemical combination of yttrium and iron (YIGF, or yttrium iron garnet filter).
[src:audio-equalization/filter-signal-processing] The garnet sits on a strip of metal driven by a transistor, and a small loop antenna touches the top of the sphere.
[src:audio-equalization/filter-signal-processing] An electromagnet changes the frequency that the garnet will pass.
[src:audio-equalization/filter-signal-processing] The advantage of this method is that the garnet can be tuned over a very wide frequency by varying the strength of the magnetic field.
[src:audio-equalization/filter-signal-processing] For even higher frequencies and greater precision, the vibrations of atoms must be used.
[src:audio-equalization/filter-signal-processing] Atomic clocks use caesium masers as ultra-high *Q* filters to stabilize their primary oscillators.
[src:audio-equalization/filter-signal-processing] Another method, used at high, fixed frequencies with very weak radio signals, is to use a ruby maser tapped delay line.
[src:audio-equalization/filter-signal-processing] The transfer function of a filter is most often defined in the domain of the complex frequencies.
[src:audio-equalization/filter-signal-processing] The back and forth passage to/from this domain is operated by the Laplace transform and its inverse (therefore, here below, the term "input signal" shall be understood as "the Laplace transform of" the time representation of the input signal, and so on).
[src:audio-equalization/filter-signal-processing] Distributed-element filters do not, in general, have rational-function transfer functions, but can approximate them.
[src:audio-equalization/filter-signal-processing] An alternative to transfer functions is to give the behavior of the filter as a convolution of the time-domain input with the filter's impulse response.
[src:audio-equalization/filter-signal-processing] The convolution theorem, which holds for Laplace transforms, guarantees equivalence with transfer functions.
[src:audio-equalization/filter-signal-processing] Certain filters may be specified by family and bandform.
[src:audio-equalization/filter-signal-processing] A filter's family is specified by the approximating polynomial used, and each leads to certain characteristics of the transfer function of the filter.
[src:audio-equalization/filter-signal-processing] Each family of filters can be specified to a particular order.
[src:audio-equalization/filter-signal-processing] The higher the order, the more the filter will approach the "ideal" filter; but also the longer the impulse response is and the longer the latency will be.
[src:audio-equalization/filter-signal-processing] Here is an image comparing Butterworth, Chebyshev, and elliptic filters.
[src:audio-equalization/filter-signal-processing] The filters in this illustration are all fifth-order low-pass filters.
[src:audio-equalization/filter-signal-processing] The particular implementation – analog or digital, passive or active – makes no difference; their output would be the same.
[src:audio-equalization/filter-signal-processing] As is clear from the image, elliptic filters are sharper than the others, but they show ripples on the whole bandwidth.
[src:audio-equalization/filter-signal-processing] Any family can be used to implement a particular bandform of which frequencies are transmitted, and which, outside the passband, are more or less attenuated.
[src:audio-equalization/filter-signal-processing] The transfer function completely specifies the behavior of a linear filter, but not the particular technology used to implement it.
[src:audio-equalization/filter-signal-processing] In other words, there are a number of different ways of achieving a particular transfer function when designing a circuit.
[src:audio-equalization/filter-signal-processing] A particular bandform of filter can be obtained by transformation of a prototype filter of that family.
[src:audio-equalization/filter-signal-processing] Impedance matching structures invariably take on the form of a filter, that is, a network of non-dissipative elements.
[src:audio-equalization/filter-signal-processing] For instance, in a passive electronics implementation, it would likely take the form of a ladder topology of inductors and capacitors.
[src:audio-equalization/filter-signal-processing] The design of matching networks shares much in common with filters and the design invariably will have a filtering action as an incidental consequence.
[src:audio-equalization/filter-signal-processing] Although the prime purpose of a matching network is not to filter, it is often the case that both functions are combined in the same circuit.
[src:audio-equalization/filter-signal-processing] The need for impedance matching does not arise while signals are in the digital domain.
[src:audio-equalization/filter-signal-processing] Similar comments can be made regarding power dividers and directional couplers.
[src:audio-equalization/filter-signal-processing] When implemented in a distributed-element format, these devices can take the form of a distributed-element filter.
[src:audio-equalization/filter-signal-processing] There are four ports to be matched and widening the bandwidth requires filter-like structures to achieve this.
[src:audio-equalization/filter-signal-processing] The inverse is also true: distributed-element filters can take the form of coupled lines.
[src:audio-equalization/infinite-impulse-response] In practice, the impulse response, even of IIR systems, usually approaches zero and can be neglected past a certain point.
[src:audio-equalization/infinite-impulse-response] However the physical systems which give rise to IIR or FIR responses are dissimilar, and therein lies the importance of the distinction.
[src:audio-equalization/infinite-impulse-response] For instance, analog electronic filters composed of resistors, capacitors, and/or inductors (and perhaps linear amplifiers) are generally IIR filters.
[src:audio-equalization/infinite-impulse-response] On the other hand, discrete-time filters (usually digital filters) based on a tapped delay line *employing no feedback* are necessarily FIR filters.
[src:audio-equalization/infinite-impulse-response] The capacitors (or inductors) in the analog filter have a "memory" and their internal state never completely relaxes following an impulse (assuming the classical model of capacitors and inductors where quantum effects are ignored).
[src:audio-equalization/infinite-impulse-response] But in the latter case, after an impulse has reached the end of the tapped delay line, the system has no further memory of that impulse and has returned to its initial state; its impulse response beyond that point is exactly zero.
[src:audio-equalization/infinite-impulse-response] Although almost all analog electronic filters are IIR, digital filters may be either IIR or FIR.
[src:audio-equalization/infinite-impulse-response] The presence of feedback in the topology of a discrete-time filter (such as the block diagram shown below) generally creates an IIR response.
[src:audio-equalization/infinite-impulse-response] The z domain transfer function of an IIR filter contains a non-trivial denominator, describing those feedback terms.
[src:audio-equalization/infinite-impulse-response] The transfer function of an FIR filter, on the other hand, has only a numerator as expressed in the general form derived below.
[src:audio-equalization/infinite-impulse-response] All of the $a_{i}$ coefficients with $i>0$ (feedback terms) are zero and the filter has no finite poles.
[src:audio-equalization/infinite-impulse-response] The transfer functions pertaining to IIR analog electronic filters have been extensively studied and optimized for their amplitude and phase characteristics.
[src:audio-equalization/infinite-impulse-response] These continuous-time filter functions are described in the Laplace domain.
[src:audio-equalization/infinite-impulse-response] Desired solutions can be transferred to the case of discrete-time filters whose transfer functions are expressed in the z domain, through the use of certain mathematical techniques such as the bilinear transform, impulse invariance, or pole–zero matching method.
[src:audio-equalization/infinite-impulse-response] Thus digital IIR filters can be based on well-known solutions for analog filters such as the Chebyshev filter, Butterworth filter, and elliptic filter, inheriting the characteristics of those solutions.
[src:audio-equalization/infinite-impulse-response] The transfer function allows one to judge whether or not a system is bounded-input, bounded-output (BIBO) stable.
[src:audio-equalization/infinite-impulse-response] To be specific, the BIBO stability criterion requires that the ROC of the system includes the unit circle.
[src:audio-equalization/infinite-impulse-response] For example, for a causal system to be stable, all poles of the transfer function have to have an absolute value smaller than one.
[src:audio-equalization/infinite-impulse-response] In other words, all poles must be located within a unit circle in the z -plane.
[src:audio-equalization/infinite-impulse-response] Clearly, if $a_{j}\neq 0$ then the poles are not located at the origin of the z -plane.
[src:audio-equalization/infinite-impulse-response] This is in contrast to the FIR filter where all poles are located at the origin, and is therefore always stable.
[src:audio-equalization/infinite-impulse-response] IIR filters are sometimes preferred over FIR filters because an IIR filter can achieve a much sharper transition region roll-off than an FIR filter of the same order.
[src:audio-equalization/infinite-impulse-response] governed by the parameter a , a real number with $0<|a|<1$ . $H(z)$ is stable and causal with a pole at a .
[src:audio-equalization/infinite-impulse-response] It can be seen that $h(n)$ is non-zero for all $n\geq 0$ , thus an impulse response which continues infinitely.
[src:audio-equalization/infinite-impulse-response] The main advantage digital IIR filters have over FIR filters is their efficiency in implementation, in order to meet a specification in terms of passband, stopband, ripple, and/or roll-off.
[src:audio-equalization/infinite-impulse-response] Such a set of specifications can be accomplished with a lower order (*Q* in the above formulae) IIR filter than would be required for an FIR filter meeting the same requirements.
[src:audio-equalization/infinite-impulse-response] If implemented in a signal processor, this implies a correspondingly fewer number of calculations per time step; the computational savings is often of a rather large factor.
[src:audio-equalization/infinite-impulse-response] On the other hand, FIR filters can be easier to design, for instance, to match a particular frequency response requirement.
[src:audio-equalization/infinite-impulse-response] This is particularly true when the requirement is not one of the usual cases (high-pass, low-pass, notch, etc.) which have been studied and optimized for analog filters.
[src:audio-equalization/infinite-impulse-response] Also FIR filters can be easily made to be linear phase (constant group delay vs frequency)—a property that is not easily met using IIR filters and then only as an approximation (for instance with the Bessel filter).
[src:audio-equalization/infinite-impulse-response] Another issue regarding digital IIR filters is the potential for limit cycle behavior when idle, due to the feedback system in conjunction with quantization.
[src:audio-equalization/infinite-impulse-response] Impulse invariance is a technique for designing discrete-time infinite-impulse-response (IIR) filters from continuous-time filters in which the impulse response of the continuous-time system is sampled to produce the impulse response of the discrete-time system.
[src:audio-equalization/infinite-impulse-response] Impulse invariance is one of the commonly used methods to meet the two basic requirements of the mapping from the s-plane to the z-plane.
[src:audio-equalization/infinite-impulse-response] This is obtained by solving the T(z) that has the same output value at the same sampling time as the analog filter, and it is only applicable when the inputs are in a pulse.
[src:audio-equalization/infinite-impulse-response] Note that all inputs of the digital filter generated by this method are approximate values, except for pulse inputs that are very accurate.
[src:audio-equalization/infinite-impulse-response] This is the simplest IIR filter design method.
[src:audio-equalization/infinite-impulse-response] It is the most accurate at low frequencies, so it is usually used in low-pass filters.
[src:audio-equalization/infinite-impulse-response] For Laplace transform or z-transform, the output after the transformation is just the input multiplied by the corresponding transformation function, T(s) or T(z).
[src:audio-equalization/infinite-impulse-response] Y(s) and Y(z) are the converted output of input X(s) and input X(z), respectively.
[src:audio-equalization/infinite-impulse-response] When applying the Laplace transform or z-transform on the unit impulse, the result is 1.
[src:audio-equalization/infinite-impulse-response] Now the output of the analog filter is just the inverse Laplace transform in the time domain.
[src:audio-equalization/infinite-impulse-response] If we use nT instead of t, we can get the output y(nT) derived from the pulse at the sampling time.
[src:audio-equalization/infinite-impulse-response] Pay attention to the fact that there is a multiplier T appearing in the formula.
[src:audio-equalization/infinite-impulse-response] This is because even if the Laplace transform and z-transform for the unit pulse are 1, the pulse itself is not necessarily the same.
[src:audio-equalization/infinite-impulse-response] For analog signals, the pulse has an infinite value but the area is 1 at t=0, but it is 1 at the discrete-time pulse t=0, so the existence of a multiplier T is required.
[src:audio-equalization/infinite-impulse-response] Step invariance is a better design method than impulse invariant.
[src:audio-equalization/infinite-impulse-response] The digital filter has several segments of input with different constants when sampling, which is composed of discrete steps.
[src:audio-equalization/infinite-impulse-response] The step invariant IIR filter is less accurate than the same input step signal to the ADC.
[src:audio-equalization/infinite-impulse-response] However, it is a better approximation for any input than the impulse invariant.
[src:audio-equalization/infinite-impulse-response] Step invariant solves the problem of the same sample values when T(z) and T(s) are both step inputs.
[src:audio-equalization/infinite-impulse-response] The input to the digital filter is u(n), and the input to the analog filter is u(t).
[src:audio-equalization/infinite-impulse-response] Apply z-transform and Laplace transform on these two inputs to obtain the converted output signal.
[src:audio-equalization/infinite-impulse-response] If sampled every T seconds, it is y(n), which is the inverse conversion of Y(z).These signals are used to solve for the digital filter and the analog filter and have the same output at the sampling time.
[src:audio-equalization/infinite-impulse-response] The following equation points out the solution of T(z), which is the approximate formula for the analog filter.
[src:audio-equalization/infinite-impulse-response] The bilinear transform is a first-order approximation of the natural logarithm function that is an exact mapping of the *z*-plane to the *s*-plane.
[src:audio-equalization/infinite-impulse-response] where T is the numerical integration step size of the trapezoidal rule used in the bilinear transform derivation; or, in other words, the sampling period.
[src:audio-equalization/infinite-impulse-response] The above bilinear approximation can be solved for s or a similar approximation for $s=(1/T)\ln(z)$ can be performed.
[src:audio-equalization/infinite-impulse-response] This relationship is used in the Laplace transfer function of any analog filter or the digital infinite impulse response (IIR) filter T(z) of the analog filter.
[src:audio-equalization/infinite-impulse-response] which is used to calculate the IIR digital filter, starting from the Laplace transfer function of the analog filter.
[src:audio-equalization/low-pass-filter] A **low-pass filter** is a filter that passes signals with a frequency lower than a selected cutoff frequency and attenuates signals with frequencies higher than the cutoff frequency.
[src:audio-equalization/low-pass-filter] The exact frequency response of the filter depends on the filter design.
[src:audio-equalization/low-pass-filter] The filter is sometimes called a **high-cut filter**, or **treble-cut filter** in audio applications.
[src:audio-equalization/low-pass-filter] A low-pass filter is the complement of a high-pass filter.
[src:audio-equalization/low-pass-filter] In optics, **high-pass** and **low-pass** may have different meanings, depending on whether referring to the frequency or wavelength of light, since these variables are inversely related.
[src:audio-equalization/low-pass-filter] High-pass frequency filters would act as low-pass wavelength filters, and vice versa.
[src:audio-equalization/low-pass-filter] For this reason, it is a good practice to refer to wavelength filters as *short-pass* and *long-pass* to avoid confusion, which would correspond to *high-pass* and *low-pass* frequencies.
[src:audio-equalization/low-pass-filter] Low-pass filters exist in many different forms, including electronic circuits such as a *hiss filter* used in audio, anti-aliasing filters for conditioning signals before analog-to-digital conversion, digital filters for smoothing sets of data, acoustic barriers, blurring of images, and so on.
[src:audio-equalization/low-pass-filter] The moving average operation used in fields such as finance is a particular kind of low-pass filter and can be analyzed with the same signal processing techniques as are used for other low-pass filters.
[src:audio-equalization/low-pass-filter] Low-pass filters provide a smoother form of a signal, removing the short-term fluctuations and leaving the longer-term trend.
[src:audio-equalization/low-pass-filter] Filter designers will often use the low-pass form as a prototype filter.
[src:audio-equalization/low-pass-filter] That is a filter with unity bandwidth and impedance.
[src:audio-equalization/low-pass-filter] The desired filter is obtained from the prototype by scaling for the desired bandwidth and impedance and transforming into the desired bandform (that is, low-pass, high-pass, band-pass or band-stop).
[src:audio-equalization/low-pass-filter] Examples of low-pass filters occur in acoustics, optics and electronics.
[src:audio-equalization/low-pass-filter] A stiff physical barrier tends to reflect higher sound frequencies, acting as an acoustic low-pass filter for transmitting sound.
[src:audio-equalization/low-pass-filter] When music is playing in another room, the low notes are easily heard, while the high notes are attenuated.
[src:audio-equalization/low-pass-filter] An optical filter with the same function can correctly be called a low-pass filter, but conventionally is called a *longpass* filter (low frequency is long wavelength), to avoid confusion.
[src:audio-equalization/low-pass-filter] In an electronic low-pass RC filter for voltage signals, high frequencies in the input signal are attenuated, but the filter has little attenuation below the cutoff frequency determined by its RC time constant.
[src:audio-equalization/low-pass-filter] For current signals, a similar circuit, using a resistor and capacitor in parallel, works in a similar manner.
[src:audio-equalization/low-pass-filter] Electronic low-pass filters are used on inputs to subwoofers and other types of loudspeakers, to block high pitches that they cannot efficiently reproduce.
[src:audio-equalization/low-pass-filter] Radio transmitters use low-pass filters to block harmonic emissions that might interfere with other communications.
[src:audio-equalization/low-pass-filter] The tone knob on many electric guitars is a low-pass filter used to reduce the amount of treble in the sound.
[src:audio-equalization/low-pass-filter] An integrator is another time constant low-pass filter.
[src:audio-equalization/low-pass-filter] Telephone lines fitted with DSL splitters use low-pass filters to separate DSL from POTS signals (and high-pass vice versa), which share the same pair of wires (*transmission channel*).
[src:audio-equalization/low-pass-filter] Low-pass filters also play a significant role in the sculpting of sound created by analogue and virtual analogue synthesisers.
[src:audio-equalization/low-pass-filter] A low-pass filter is used as an anti-aliasing filter before sampling and for reconstruction in digital-to-analog conversion.
[src:audio-equalization/low-pass-filter] An ideal low-pass filter completely eliminates all frequencies above the cutoff frequency while passing those below unchanged; its frequency response is a rectangular function and is a brick-wall filter.
[src:audio-equalization/low-pass-filter] The transition region present in practical filters does not exist in an ideal filter.
[src:audio-equalization/low-pass-filter] An ideal low-pass filter can be realized mathematically (theoretically) by multiplying a signal by the rectangular function in the frequency domain or, equivalently, convolution with its impulse response, a sinc function, in the time domain.
[src:audio-equalization/low-pass-filter] However, the ideal filter is impossible to realize without also having signals of infinite extent in time, and so generally needs to be approximated for real ongoing signals, because the sinc function's support region extends to all past and future times.
[src:audio-equalization/low-pass-filter] The filter would therefore need to have infinite delay, or knowledge of the infinite future and past, to perform the convolution.
[src:audio-equalization/low-pass-filter] It is effectively realizable for pre-recorded digital signals by assuming extensions of zero into the past and future, or, more typically, by making the signal repetitive and using Fourier analysis.
[src:audio-equalization/low-pass-filter] This delay is manifested as phase shift.
[src:audio-equalization/low-pass-filter] Greater accuracy in approximation requires a longer delay.
[src:audio-equalization/low-pass-filter] Truncating an ideal low-pass filter result in ringing artifacts via the Gibbs phenomenon, which can be reduced or worsened by the choice of windowing function.
[src:audio-equalization/low-pass-filter] Design and choice of real filters involves understanding and minimizing these artifacts.
[src:audio-equalization/low-pass-filter] For example, simple truncation of the sinc function will create severe ringing artifacts, which can be reduced using window functions that drop off more smoothly at the edges.
[src:audio-equalization/low-pass-filter] The time response of a low-pass filter is found by solving the response to the simple low-pass RC filter.
[src:audio-equalization/low-pass-filter] where $\omega _{0}={1 \over RC}$ is the cutoff frequency of the filter.
[src:audio-equalization/low-pass-filter] The most common way to characterize the frequency response of a circuit is to find its Laplace transform transfer function, $H(s)={V_{\rm {out}}(s) \over V_{\rm {in}}(s)}$ .
[src:audio-equalization/low-pass-filter] A discrete difference equation is easily obtained by sampling the step input response above at regular intervals of $nT$ where $n=0,1,...$ and T is the time between samples.
[src:audio-equalization/low-pass-filter] Comparing the reconstructed output signal from the difference equation, $V_{n}=\beta V_{n-1}+(1-\beta )v_{n}$ , to the step input response, $v_{\text{out}}(t)=V_{i}(1-e^{-\omega _{0}t})$ , we find that there is an exact reconstruction (0% error).
[src:audio-equalization/low-pass-filter] This is the reconstructed output for a time-invariant input.
[src:audio-equalization/low-pass-filter] However, if the input is *time variant*, such as $v_{\text{in}}(t)=V_{i}\sin(\omega t)$ , this model approximates the input signal as a series of step functions with duration T producing an error in the reconstructed output signal.
[src:audio-equalization/low-pass-filter] The error produced from *time variant* inputs is difficult to quantify but decreases as $T\rightarrow 0$ .
[src:audio-equalization/low-pass-filter] Many digital filters are designed to give low-pass characteristics.
[src:audio-equalization/low-pass-filter] Both infinite impulse response and finite impulse response low pass filters, as well as filters using Fourier transforms, are widely used.
[src:audio-equalization/low-pass-filter] The effect of an infinite impulse response low-pass filter can be simulated on a computer by analyzing an RC filter's behavior in the time domain, and then discretizing the model.
[src:audio-equalization/low-pass-filter] where $Q_{c}(t)$ is the charge stored in the capacitor at time t.
[src:audio-equalization/low-pass-filter] For simplicity, assume that samples of the input and output are taken at evenly spaced points in time separated by $\Delta _{T}$ time.
[src:audio-equalization/low-pass-filter] By definition, the *smoothing factor* is within the range $0\;\leq \;\alpha \;\leq \;1$ .
[src:audio-equalization/low-pass-filter] If α=0.5, then the *RC* time constant equals the sampling period.
[src:audio-equalization/low-pass-filter] If $\alpha \;\ll \;0.5$ , then *RC* is significantly larger than the sampling interval, and $\Delta _{T}\;\approx \;\alpha RC$ .
[src:audio-equalization/low-pass-filter] The filter recurrence relation provides a way to determine the output samples in terms of the input samples and the preceding output.
[src:audio-equalization/low-pass-filter] That is, the change from one filter output to the next is proportional to the difference between the previous output and the next input.
[src:audio-equalization/low-pass-filter] This exponential smoothing property matches the exponential decay seen in the continuous-time system.
[src:audio-equalization/low-pass-filter] As expected, as the time constant *RC* increases, the discrete-time smoothing parameter $\alpha$ decreases, and the output samples $(y_{1},\,y_{2},\,\ldots ,\,y_{n})$ respond more slowly to a change in the input samples $(x_{1},\,x_{2},\,\ldots ,\,x_{n})$ ; the system has more *inertia*.
[src:audio-equalization/low-pass-filter] This filter is an infinite-impulse-response (IIR) single-pole low-pass filter.
[src:audio-equalization/low-pass-filter] Finite-impulse-response filters can be built that approximate the sinc function time-domain response of an ideal sharp-cutoff low-pass filter.
[src:audio-equalization/low-pass-filter] For minimum distortion, the finite impulse response filter has an unbounded number of coefficients operating on an unbounded signal.
[src:audio-equalization/low-pass-filter] In practice, the time-domain response must be time truncated and is often of a simplified shape; in the simplest case, a running average can be used, giving a square time response.
[src:audio-equalization/low-pass-filter] For non-realtime filtering, to achieve a low pass filter, the entire signal is usually taken as a looped signal, the Fourier transform is taken, filtered in the frequency domain, followed by an inverse Fourier transform.
[src:audio-equalization/low-pass-filter] Only O(n log(n)) operations are required compared to O(n2) for the time domain filtering algorithm.
[src:audio-equalization/low-pass-filter] This can also sometimes be done in real time, where the signal is delayed long enough to perform the Fourier transformation on shorter, overlapping blocks.
[src:audio-equalization/low-pass-filter] There are many different types of filter circuits, with different responses to changing frequency.
[src:audio-equalization/low-pass-filter] The frequency response of a filter is generally represented using a Bode plot, and the filter is characterized by its cutoff frequency and rate of frequency rolloff.
[src:audio-equalization/low-pass-filter] In all cases, at the *cutoff frequency,* the filter attenuates the input power by half or 3 dB.
[src:audio-equalization/low-pass-filter] So the **order** of the filter determines the amount of additional attenuation for frequencies higher than the cutoff frequency.
[src:audio-equalization/low-pass-filter] On any Butterworth filter, if one extends the horizontal line to the right and the diagonal line to the upper-left (the asymptotes of the function), they intersect at exactly the *cutoff frequency*, 3 dB below the horizontal line.
[src:audio-equalization/low-pass-filter] The various types of filters (Butterworth filter, Chebyshev filter, Bessel filter, etc.) all have different-looking *knee curves*.
[src:audio-equalization/low-pass-filter] Many second-order filters have "peaking" or resonance that puts their frequency response *above* the horizontal line at this peak.
[src:audio-equalization/low-pass-filter] The meanings of 'low' and 'high'—that is, the cutoff frequency—depend on the characteristics of the filter.
[src:audio-equalization/low-pass-filter] The term "low-pass filter" merely refers to the shape of the filter's response; a high-pass filter could be built that cuts off at a lower frequency than any low-pass filter—it is their responses that set them apart.
[src:audio-equalization/low-pass-filter] Electronic circuits can be devised for any desired frequency range, right up through microwave frequencies (above 1 GHz) and higher.
[src:audio-equalization/low-pass-filter] Continuous-time filters can also be described in terms of the Laplace transform of their impulse response, in a way that makes it easy to analyze all characteristics of the filter by considering the pattern of poles and zeros of the Laplace transform in the complex plane.
[src:audio-equalization/low-pass-filter] where *H* is the transfer function, *s* is the Laplace transform variable (complex angular frequency), *τ* is the filter time constant, $\alpha$ is the cutoff frequency, and *K* is the gain of the filter in the passband.
[src:audio-equalization/low-pass-filter] One simple low-pass filter circuit consists of a resistor in series with a load, and a capacitor in parallel with the load.
[src:audio-equalization/low-pass-filter] The capacitor exhibits reactance, and blocks low-frequency signals, forcing them through the load instead.
[src:audio-equalization/low-pass-filter] At higher frequencies, the reactance drops, and the capacitor effectively functions as a short circuit.
[src:audio-equalization/low-pass-filter] The combination of resistance and capacitance gives the time constant of the filter $\tau \;=\;RC$ (represented by the Greek letter tau).
[src:audio-equalization/low-pass-filter] The capacitor is not an "on/off" object (like the block or pass fluidic explanation above).
[src:audio-equalization/low-pass-filter] The capacitor variably acts between these two extremes.
[src:audio-equalization/low-pass-filter] It is the Bode plot and frequency response that show this variability.
[src:audio-equalization/low-pass-filter] A resistor–inductor circuit or RL filter is an electric circuit composed of resistors and inductors driven by a voltage or current source.
[src:audio-equalization/low-pass-filter] A first-order RL circuit is composed of one resistor and one inductor and is the simplest type of RL circuit.
[src:audio-equalization/low-pass-filter] A first-order RL circuit is one of the simplest analogue infinite impulse response electronic filters.
[src:audio-equalization/low-pass-filter] It consists of a resistor and an inductor, either in series driven by a voltage source or in parallel driven by a current source.
[src:audio-equalization/low-pass-filter] An RLC circuit (the letters R, L, and C can be in a different sequence) is an electrical circuit consisting of a resistor, an inductor, and a capacitor, connected in series or in parallel.
[src:audio-equalization/low-pass-filter] The RLC part of the name is due to those letters being the usual electrical symbols for resistance, inductance, and capacitance, respectively.
[src:audio-equalization/low-pass-filter] The circuit forms a harmonic oscillator for current and will resonate in a similar way as an LC circuit will.
[src:audio-equalization/low-pass-filter] The main difference that the presence of the resistor makes is that any oscillation induced in the circuit will die away over time if it is not kept going by a source.
[src:audio-equalization/low-pass-filter] This effect of the resistor is called damping.
[src:audio-equalization/low-pass-filter] The presence of the resistance also reduces the peak resonant frequency somewhat.
[src:audio-equalization/low-pass-filter] Some resistance is unavoidable in real circuits, even if a resistor is not specifically included as a component.
[src:audio-equalization/low-pass-filter] An ideal, pure LC circuit is an abstraction for the purpose of theory.
[src:audio-equalization/low-pass-filter] There are many applications for this circuit.
[src:audio-equalization/low-pass-filter] They are used in many different types of oscillator circuits.
[src:audio-equalization/low-pass-filter] Another important application is for tuning, such as in radio receivers or television sets, where they are used to select a narrow range of frequencies from the ambient radio waves.
[src:audio-equalization/low-pass-filter] In this role, the circuit is often called a tuned circuit.
[src:audio-equalization/low-pass-filter] An RLC circuit can be used as a band-pass filter, band-stop filter, low-pass filter, or high-pass filter.
[src:audio-equalization/low-pass-filter] The RLC filter is described as a *second-order* circuit, meaning that any voltage or current in the circuit can be described by a second-order differential equation in circuit analysis.
[src:audio-equalization/low-pass-filter] The transfer function $H_{LP}(f)$ of a second-order low-pass filter can be expressed as a function of frequency f as shown in Equation 1, the Second-Order Low-Pass Filter Standard Form.
[src:audio-equalization/low-pass-filter] In this equation, f is the frequency variable, $f_{c}$ is the cutoff frequency, $f_{FSF}$ is the frequency scaling factor, and Q is the quality factor.
[src:audio-equalization/low-pass-filter] Equation 1 describes three regions of operation: below cutoff, in the area of cutoff, and above cutoff.
[src:audio-equalization/low-pass-filter] With attenuation at frequencies above $f_{c}$ increasing by a power of two, the last formula describes a second-order low-pass filter.
[src:audio-equalization/low-pass-filter] The frequency scaling factor $f_{FSF}$ is used to scale the cutoff frequency of the filter so that it follows the definitions given before.
[src:audio-equalization/low-pass-filter] Higher-order passive filters can also be constructed (see diagram for a third-order example).
[src:audio-equalization/low-pass-filter] An *active* low-pass filter adds an active device to create an active filter that allows for gain in the passband.
[src:audio-equalization/low-pass-filter] The gain in the passband is −*R*2/*R*1, and the stopband drops off at −6 dB per octave (that is −20 dB per decade) as it is a first-order filter.
[src:audio-equalization/q-factor] In physics and engineering, the **quality factor** or **Q factor** is a dimensionless parameter that describes how underdamped an oscillator or resonator is.
[src:audio-equalization/q-factor] Resonators with high quality factors have low damping, so that they ring or vibrate longer.
[src:audio-equalization/q-factor] For example, a pendulum suspended from a precision bearing, oscillating in air, has a high Q, while a pendulum immersed in oil has a low one.
[src:audio-equalization/q-factor] There are two definitions of Q that give numerically similar, but not identical, results.
[src:audio-equalization/q-factor] The more general definition is the ratio of the initial energy stored in the resonator to the energy lost in one radian of the cycle of oscillation.
[src:audio-equalization/q-factor] An alternative definition of Q factor, more applicable to high Q oscillators, is as the ratio of a resonator's centre frequency to its bandwidth when subject to an oscillating driving force.
[src:audio-equalization/q-factor] The Q factor is a parameter that describes the resonance behavior of a damped harmonic oscillator (resonator).
[src:audio-equalization/q-factor] Sinusoidally driven resonators having higher Q factors resonate with greater amplitudes (at the resonant frequency) but have a smaller range of frequencies around that frequency for which they resonate; the range of frequencies for which the oscillator resonates is called the bandwidth.
[src:audio-equalization/q-factor] Thus, a high-Q tuned circuit in a radio receiver would be more difficult to tune, but would have more selectivity; it would do a better job of filtering out signals from other stations that lie nearby on the spectrum.
[src:audio-equalization/q-factor] High-Q oscillators oscillate with a smaller range of frequencies and are more stable.
[src:audio-equalization/q-factor] The quality factor of devices varies substantially from system to system, depending on their function and design.
[src:audio-equalization/q-factor] Systems for which damping is important (such as dampers keeping a door from slamming shut) have Q near 1⁄2.
[src:audio-equalization/q-factor] Clocks, lasers, and other resonating systems that need either strong resonance or high frequency stability have high quality factors.
[src:audio-equalization/q-factor] Tuning forks have quality factors around 1000.
[src:audio-equalization/q-factor] The quality factor of atomic clocks, superconducting RF cavities used in accelerators, and some high-Q lasers can reach 1011 and higher.
[src:audio-equalization/q-factor] There are many alternative quantities used by physicists and engineers to describe how damped an oscillator is.
[src:audio-equalization/q-factor] Important examples include: the damping ratio, relative bandwidth, linewidth and bandwidth measured in octaves.
[src:audio-equalization/q-factor] Johnson of Western Electric Company's Engineering Department while evaluating the quality of coils (inductors).
[src:audio-equalization/q-factor] His choice of the symbol Q was only because, at the time, all other letters of the alphabet were taken.
[src:audio-equalization/q-factor] The term was not intended as an abbreviation for "quality" or "quality factor", although these terms have grown to be associated with it.
[src:audio-equalization/q-factor] The definition of Q since its first use in 1914 has been generalized to apply to coils and condensers, resonant circuits, resonant devices, resonant transmission lines, cavity resonators,.
[src:audio-equalization/q-factor] It has expanded beyond the electronics field to apply to dynamical systems in general: mechanical and acoustic resonators, material Q and quantum systems such as spectral lines and particle resonances, and optical resonators such as laser cavities.
[src:audio-equalization/q-factor] There are two common definitions for Q, which apply generally to all these systems but are not exactly equivalent.
[src:audio-equalization/q-factor] They become approximately equivalent as Q becomes larger, meaning the resonator becomes less damped.
[src:audio-equalization/q-factor] Under this definition, Q is the reciprocal of fractional bandwidth.
[src:audio-equalization/q-factor] The factor 2*π* makes Q expressible in simpler terms, involving only the coefficients of the second-order differential equation describing most resonant systems, electrical or mechanical.
[src:audio-equalization/q-factor] In electrical systems, the stored energy is the sum of energies stored in lossless inductors and capacitors; the lost energy is the sum of the energies dissipated in resistors per cycle.
[src:audio-equalization/q-factor] In mechanical systems, the stored energy is the sum of the potential and kinetic energies at some point in time; the lost energy is the work done by an external force, per cycle, to maintain amplitude.
[src:audio-equalization/q-factor] where ω is the angular frequency at which the stored energy and power loss are measured.
[src:audio-equalization/q-factor] This definition is consistent with its usage in describing circuits with a single reactive element (capacitor or inductor), where it can be shown to be equal to the ratio of reactive power to real power.
[src:audio-equalization/q-factor] The Q-factor determines the qualitative behavior of simple damped oscillators.
[src:audio-equalization/q-factor] Starting from the stored energy definition, it can be shown that $Q={\frac {1}{2\zeta }}$ , where $\zeta$ is the damping ratio.
[src:audio-equalization/q-factor] In negative feedback systems, the dominant closed-loop response is often well-modeled by a second-order system.
[src:audio-equalization/q-factor] The phase margin of the open-loop system sets the quality factor Q of the closed-loop system; as the phase margin decreases, the approximate second-order closed-loop system is made more oscillatory (i.e., has a higher quality factor).
[src:audio-equalization/q-factor] Physically speaking, Q is approximately the ratio of the stored energy to the energy dissipated over one radian of the oscillation; or nearly equivalently, at high enough Q values, 2π times the ratio of the total energy stored and the energy lost in a single cycle.
[src:audio-equalization/q-factor] It is a dimensionless parameter that compares the exponential time constant τ for decay of an oscillating physical system's amplitude to its oscillation period.
[src:audio-equalization/q-factor] Equivalently, it compares the frequency at which a system oscillates to the rate at which it dissipates its energy.
[src:audio-equalization/q-factor] More precisely, the frequency and period used should be based on the system's natural frequency, which at low Q values is somewhat higher than the oscillation frequency as measured by zero crossings.
[src:audio-equalization/q-factor] Equivalently (for large values of Q), the Q factor is approximately the number of oscillations required for a freely oscillating system's energy to fall off to *e*−2*π*, or about 1⁄535 or 0.2%, of its original energy.
[src:audio-equalization/q-factor] This means the amplitude falls off to approximately *e*−*π* or 4% of its original amplitude.
[src:audio-equalization/q-factor] The width (bandwidth) of the resonance is given by (approximately): $\Delta f={\frac {f_{\mathrm {N} }}{Q}},\,$ where *f*N is the natural frequency, and Δ*f*, the bandwidth, is the width of the range of frequencies for which the energy is at least half its peak value.
[src:audio-equalization/q-factor] The energy of oscillation, or the power dissipation, decays twice as fast, that is, as the square of the amplitude, as *e*−2*αt* or *e*−2*t/τ*.
[src:audio-equalization/q-factor] For this system, when *Q* > ⁠1/2⁠ (i.e., when the system is underdamped), it has two complex conjugate poles that each have a real part of −α.
[src:audio-equalization/q-factor] That is, the attenuation parameter α represents the rate of exponential decay of the oscillations (that is, of the output after an impulse) into the system.
[src:audio-equalization/q-factor] A higher quality factor implies a lower attenuation rate, and so high-Q systems oscillate for many cycles.
[src:audio-equalization/q-factor] For example, high-quality bells have an approximately pure sinusoidal tone for a long time after being struck by a hammer.
[src:audio-equalization/q-factor] For an electrically resonant system, the *Q* factor represents the effect of electrical resistance and, for electromechanical resonators such as quartz crystals, mechanical friction.
[src:audio-equalization/q-factor] The 2-sided bandwidth relative to a resonant frequency of *F*0 (Hz) is ${\frac {F_{0}}{Q}}$ .
[src:audio-equalization/q-factor] For example, an antenna tuned to have a Q value of 10 and a centre frequency of 100 kHz would have a 3 dB bandwidth of 10 kHz.
[src:audio-equalization/q-factor] In audio, bandwidth is often expressed in terms of octaves.
[src:audio-equalization/q-factor] where R, L, and C are the resistance, inductance and capacitance of the tuned circuit, respectively.
[src:audio-equalization/q-factor] Larger series resistances correspond to lower circuit Q values.
[src:audio-equalization/q-factor] Consider a circuit where R, L, and C are all in parallel.
[src:audio-equalization/q-factor] The lower the parallel resistance is, the more effect it will have in damping the circuit and thus result in lower Q.
[src:audio-equalization/q-factor] This is useful in filter design to determine the bandwidth.
[src:audio-equalization/q-factor] In a parallel LC circuit where the main loss is the resistance of the inductor, R, in series with the inductance, L, Q is as in the series circuit.
[src:audio-equalization/q-factor] This is a common circumstance for resonators, where limiting the resistance of the inductor to improve Q and narrow the bandwidth is the desired result.
[src:audio-equalization/q-factor] The Q of an individual reactive component depends on the frequency at which it is evaluated, which is typically the resonant frequency of the circuit that it is used in.
[src:audio-equalization/q-factor] The Q of an inductor with a series loss resistance is the Q of a resonant circuit using that inductor (including its series loss) and a perfect capacitor.
[src:audio-equalization/q-factor] For a single damped mass-spring system, the Q factor represents the effect of simplified viscous damping or drag, where the damping force or drag force is proportional to velocity.
[src:audio-equalization/q-factor] The formula for the Q factor is: $Q={\frac {\sqrt {Mk}}{D}},\,$ where M is the mass, k is the spring constant, and D is the damping coefficient, defined by the equation *F*damping = −*Dv*, where v is the velocity.
[src:audio-equalization/q-factor] The Q of a musical instrument is critical; an excessively high Q in a resonator will not evenly amplify the multiple frequencies an instrument produces.
[src:audio-equalization/q-factor] For this reason, string instruments often have bodies with complex shapes, so that they produce a wide range of frequencies fairly evenly.
[src:audio-equalization/q-factor] The Q of a brass instrument or wind instrument needs to be high enough to pick one frequency out of the broader-spectrum buzzing of the lips or reed.
[src:audio-equalization/q-factor] By contrast, a vuvuzela is made of flexible plastic, and therefore has a very low Q for a brass instrument, giving it a muddy, breathy tone.
[src:audio-equalization/q-factor] Instruments made of stiffer plastic, brass, or wood have higher Q values.
[src:audio-equalization/q-factor] An excessively high Q can make it harder to hit a note.
[src:audio-equalization/q-factor] Q in an instrument may vary across frequencies, but this may not be desirable.
[src:audio-equalization/q-factor] Helmholtz resonators have a very high Q, as they are designed for picking out a very narrow range of frequencies.
[src:audio-equalization/q-factor] In optics, the Q factor of a resonant cavity is given by $Q={\frac {2\pi f_{o}\,E}{P}},\,$ where fo is the resonant frequency, E is the stored energy in the cavity, and *P* = −⁠*dE*/*dt*⁠ is the power dissipated.
[src:audio-equalization/q-factor] The optical Q is equal to the ratio of the resonant frequency to the bandwidth of the cavity resonance.
[src:audio-equalization/q-factor] The average lifetime of a resonant photon in the cavity is proportional to the cavity's Q.
[src:audio-equalization/q-factor] If the Q factor of a laser's cavity is abruptly changed from a low value to a high one, the laser will emit a pulse of light that is much more intense than the laser's normal continuous output.
[src:audio-equalization/q-factor] Q factor is of particular importance in plasmonics, where loss is linked to the damping of the surface plasmon resonance.
[src:audio-equalization/q-factor] While loss is normally considered a hindrance in the development of plasmonic devices, it is possible to leverage this property to present new enhanced functionalities.
